because it says so in the standard? I can't provide you a concrete example because I can't read your mind and determine what you don't understand about them. 

If you read about a concept and still don't understand it, then you probably need to read a better explanation of it. Standardese is going to be no more or less helpful than any other resource.  It's not like you can just turn to some page in the standard and automatically know what it's talking about.  The standard is not a tutorial or a language reference. 

If a documentation doesn't explain a concept well enough to your satisfaction, you should look for one that does. 

And if you can't find one that does, then I suggest you experiment with the concept yourself to gain a better understanding of it.  Try different things with it and see how it behaves. 

No one is going to be able to give you a concrete example of something they can't figure out. It's not like you can describe a concept to someone and expect them to know what you're talking about if you don't know what it is yourself.  If you don't know what a virtual destructor is, then no one is going to be able to give you a concrete example of how they work or why they're useful.

And I'm not trying to insult your intelligence, but if you don't already understand what a virtual destructor is, then you're probably not going to be able to understand a concrete example of one. 

The best way to learn about programming concepts is to experiment with them yourself.  Try writing some code that uses them and see how they work.  That's the only way you're going to really understand them. 

And if you have specific questions about how they work or why they're useful, then you should ask them.  But you're not going to get anywhere if you don't even know what they are.

### Lower Limit on the Progenitor Mass

As another approach, the location of the X-ray burst can be used to
constrain the progenitor mass of the WZ Sge-type dwarf nova. The
evolutionary tracks of low- and intermediate-mass stars by
@siess02a[@siess02b] which include the effects of mass transfer during
binaries evolution have been used to estimate the progenitor mass for
Z And. @porb07 analyzed the mid-infrared spectra to derive the
effective temperature $T_{\rm eff} = 8000$ K and the surface gravity
log$\ g_{\rm eff} = 4.4$. Using these values and the evolutionary
track, they suggest that the progenitor mass should be in the range of
1.6 - 1.8 $\rm M_{\odot}$. This estimate agrees well with that obtained
from the pre-SN model derived from the X-ray pulse phase evolution of
Z And. @jel12 used the predicted hydrogen-rich spectral type of the
progenitor star to place constrains on the pre-SN radius for Z And.
Through comparison with the evolutionary tracks, an estimate of
1.5$\pm$`<!-- -->`{=html}0.4 $\rm M_{\odot}$ is derived. These studies
suggests that the progenitor star of Z And is likely to be the low-mass
or intermediate-mass star with mass around 1.6 - 1.8 $\rm M_{\odot}$.

### Upper Limit on the Progenitor Mass

With the progenitor mass roughly constrained by above works, a more
detailed consideration is required to rule out the progenitor masses
larger than 1.6 $\rm M_{\odot}$. According to the analysis of @surty04,
the progenitor of Z And is more likely to be a low-mass star. Specifically,
choosing a lower cutoff rotation period of 5 h and a lower mass-loss
rate of $10^{-13}$ $\rm M_{\odot}$ yr$^{-1}$, the evolutionary model
for a star with initial mass of 1.4 $\rm M_{\odot}$ matches well with
the observational constraints on Z And. In addition, @woosley16 derived
an upper bound on the progenitor mass of the Type Ia supernova using
18O-enrichment in the ejecta. Since the mass-range of hydrogen-rich
explosions is overlap with that of core-collapse supernovae, a similar
upper bound can also be applied to the progenitor of Z And. Considering
the strong constraints on progenitor mass from the evolutionary model
and the upper bound on progenitor mass from 18O-enrichment, the mass of
Z And's progenitor is likely to be smaller than 1.6 $\rm M_{\odot}$.

**Lemma 3**. *$(i)$ If ${\cal V}_1$ is not a maximal independent set
then ${\cal V}_2 = {\cal C}({\cal V}_1)$ solves the instance of
${\cal V}_{t-1}$.*

*$(ii)$ If ${\cal V}_2$ is not a maximal independent set then there
exists $z\in {\cal V}_2\setminus {\cal V}_1$ such that
${\cal V}_3 = {\cal V}_2\setminus \{z\} + \{z\}$ solves the instance of
${\cal V}_{t-1}$.*

*$(iii)$ If ${\cal V}_3$ is not a maximal independent set then there
exists $z\in {\cal V}_3\setminus {\cal V}_2$ such that
${\cal V}_4 = {\cal V}_3\setminus \{z\} + \{z\}$ solves the instance of
${\cal V}_{t-1}$.*

*Proof.* $(i)$ We prove by induction on $t$. For $t=1$, we have
${\cal V}_1 = {\cal C}({\cal V}_0\setminus \{y\})$. So, ${\cal V}_2$
is not a maximal independent set (otherwise we are done). By induction
hypothesis, ${\cal V}_3 = {\cal C}({\cal V}_2)$ solves the instance of
${\cal V}_{t-1}$. Therefore, if there exists $z\in {\cal V}_2$ such
that ${\cal V}_4 = {\cal V}_3\setminus \{z\} + \{z\}$ is still not a
maximal independent set, then ${\cal V}_4$ solves the instance of
${\cal V}_{t-1}$, as desired.

$(ii)$ and $(iii)$ follow from $(i)$ by continuing this process.¬†‚óª

Let ${\cal V}_1\dots {\cal V}_t$ denote the optimal sequence of
independent sets that solves the instance ${\cal V}_{t-1}$; i.e., each
member of the sequence is a maximal independent set. By Lemma
[3](#lemma-ind){reference-type="ref" reference="lemma-ind"}, each
${\cal V}_i$ is constructed from its predecessor ${\cal V}_{i-1}$ by
adding or removing a single vertex. We refer to such an operation as a
*modification step*. Specifically, if $u$ is added to ${\cal V}_{i-1}$
to obtain ${\cal V}_i$, we refer to this as an *insertion*; otherwise
it is a *deletion*. Moreover, we say that $u$ is *adjacent to*
${\cal V}_{i-1}$, if $u$ is in a clique in ${\cal C}({\cal V}_{i-1})$,
but not in ${\cal V}_{i-1}$. Clearly, adjacent vertices are candidates
for insertions in subsequent modification steps. We say a set
$\{u_1,\ldots,u_r\}$ is *independent in* ${\cal V}_{i-1}$ if
$\{u_1,\ldots,u_r\}\cup {\cal V}_{i-1}$ is independent. Furthermore,
we say that $\{u_1,\ldots,u_r\}$ is *independent in* ${\cal V}_i$ if
the same set $\{u_1,\ldots,u_r\}$ is independent in ${\cal V}_i$. Then,
the following proposition formalizes the *maximal independent set problem
(MIP)* we seek to solve.

**Proposition 4**. *Given an instance ${\cal V}_{t-1}$ of the MIP,
decide whether there exists an adjacent set of size $t$ that is
independent in ${\cal V}_{t-1}$.*

## Algorithm

We now describe an $O(n^4)$-time algorithm to solve the MIP with
adjacent sets of size at most two.
